# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hashicorp-consul
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] HashiCorp Consul is a service networking solution that enables teams to manage secure network connectivity between services and across on-prem and multi-cloud environments and runtimes.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul offers service discovery, service mesh, traffic management, and automated updates to network infrastructure devices.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can use these features individually or together in a single Consul deployment.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul provides a *control plane* that enables you to register, query, and secure services deployed across your network.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] The control plane is the part of the network infrastructure that maintains a central registry to track services and their respective IP addresses.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] It is a distributed system that runs on clusters of nodes, such as physical servers, cloud instances, virtual machines, or containers.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul interacts with the *data plane* through proxies.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] The data plane is the part of the network infrastructure that processes data requests.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul increases application resilience, bolsters uptime, accelerates application deployment, and improves security across service-to-service communications.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] HashiCorp co-founder and CTO Armon Dadgar explains how Consul solves networking challenges.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] To learn more about Consul and how it compares to similar products, refer to Consul use cases.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Adopting a microservices architecture on cloud infrastructure is a critical step toward delivering value at scale, but knowing where healthy services are running on your networks in real time becomes a challenge.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul automates service discovery by replacing service connections usually handled with load balancers with an identity-based service catalog.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] The service catalog is a centralized source of truth that you can query through Consul’s DNS server or API.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] The catalog always knows which services are available, which have been removed, and which services are healthy.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul supports both IPv4 and IPv6 networks.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] To learn more about Consul's service discovery features and how they compares to similar products, refer to Consul compared to other DNS tools.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Modern organizations may deploy services to a combination of on-prem infrastructure environments and public cloud providers across multiple regions.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Services may run on bare metal, virtual machines, or as containers across Kubernetes clusters.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul routes network traffic to any runtime or infrastructure environment your services need to reach.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can also use Consul API Gateway to route traffic into and out of the network.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul service mesh provides additional capabilities, such as securing communication between services, traffic management, and observability, with no application code changes.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul also has many integrations with Kubernetes that enable you to leverage Consul features in containerized environments.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] For example, Consul can automatically inject sidecar proxies into Kubernetes Pods and sync Kubernetes Services and non-Kubernetes services into the Consul service registry without manual changes to the application or changing the Pod definition.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can also schedule Consul workloads with HashiCorp Nomad to provide secure service-to-service communication between Nomad jobs and task groups.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Microservice architectures are complex and difficult to secure against accidental disclosure to malicious actors.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] When you deploy Consul to Kubernetes clusters, you can also integrate with HashiCorp Vault to manage sensitive data.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] By default, Consul on Kubernetes leverages Kubernetes secrets as the backend system.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Kubernetes secrets are base64 encoded, unencrypted, and lack lease or time-to-live properties.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] By leveraging Vault as a secrets backend for Consul on Kubernetes, you can manage and store Consul related secrets within a centralized Vault cluster to use across one or many Consul on Kubernetes datacenters.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Refer to Vault as the Secrets Backend for additional information.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can also secure your Consul deployment, itself, by defining security policies in access control lists (ACL) to control access to data and Consul APIs.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Outages are unavoidable, but with distributed systems it is critical that a power failure in one datacenter doesn’t disrupt downstream service operations.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can enable automated backups, redundancy zones, read-replicas, and other features that prevent data loss and downtime after a catastrophic event.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] L7 observability features also deliver service traffic metrics in the Consul UI, which help you understand the state of a service and its connections within the mesh.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Change to your network, including day-to-day operational tasks such as updating network device endpoints and firewall or load balancer rules, can lead to problems that disrupt operations at critical moments.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] You can deploy the Consul-Terraform-Sync (CTS) add-on to dynamically update network infrastructure devices when a service changes.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] CTS monitors the service information stored in Consul and automatically launches an instance of HashiCorp Terraform to drive relevant changes to the network infrastructure when Consul registers a change, reducing the manual effort of configuring network infrastructure.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Rolling out changes can be risky, especially in complex network environments.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Updated services may not behave as expected when connected to other services, resulting in upstream or downstream issues.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] Consul service mesh supports layer 7 (L7) traffic management, which lets you divide L7 traffic into different subsets of service instances.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] This enables you to divide your pool of services for canary testing, A/B tests, blue/green deployments, and soft multi-tenancy (prod/qa/staging sharing compute resources) deployments.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] HashiCorp offers core Consul functionality for free in the community edition, which is ideal for smaller businesses and teams that want to pilot Consul within their organizations.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] As your business grows, you can upgrade to Consul Enterprise, which offers additional capabilities designed to address organizational complexities of collaboration, operations, scale, and governance.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-intro] We welcome questions, suggestions, and contributions from the community.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-software] Consul was initially released in 2014 as a service discovery platform.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-software] In addition to service discovery, it now provides a full-featured service mesh for secure service segmentation across any cloud or runtime environment, and distributed key–value storage for application configuration.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-software] Registered services and nodes can be queried using a DNS interface or an HTTP interface.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-software] Envoy proxy provides security, observability, and resilience for all application traffic.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul-software] HashiCorp announced on August 10, 2023, that it changed the license of its software from the MPL license to the Business Source License 1.1.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] Consul is a networking tool that provides comprehensive service discovery and service mesh solutions.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] It solves networking and security challenges when operating microservices and cloud infrastructure in multi-cloud and hybrid cloud environments at any scale.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] This documentation describes Consul, provides usage workflows for Consul operations and service networking scenarios, and includes specification and API references to help you build custom automated solutions for your network.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] Consul is a service networking platform with many features for securing your service communications and automating network service management.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] Consul supports many application runtimes and cloud platforms, and enables service networking in hybrid and multi-cloud environments.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] If you are new to Consul, these resources can help you learn about Consul and quickly get started with its service networking features.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] The processes to install and manage Consul as a long-running daemon on multiple nodes in a network.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] The processes to register services and use Consul's service discovery and service mesh features with your application workloads.
[src:hashicorp-consul/consul] Manage your network by configuring Consul agents, service definitions, health checks, as well as service mesh behavior and application configuration.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp is headquartered in San Francisco, but its employees are distributed across the United States, Canada, Australia, India, and Europe.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp offers source-available libraries and other proprietary products.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp was founded in 2012 by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, two classmates from the University of Washington's Paul G.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Allen School of Computer Science and Engineering .
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Co-founder Hashimoto was previously working on open-source software called Vagrant, which became incorporated into HashiCorp.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] On 29 November 2021, HashiCorp set terms for its IPO at $68-$72 at a valuation of $13 billion.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp considers its workers to be remote workers first rather than coming into an office on a full-time basis.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Around April 2021, a supply chain attack using code auditing tool codecov allowed hackers limited access to HashiCorp's customers networks.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] As a result, private credentials were leaked.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp revoked a private signing key and asked its customers to use a new rotated key.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Mitchell Hashimoto resigned from the company in December 2023.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] On April 24, 2024, the company announced it had entered into an agreement to be acquired by IBM for $6.4 billion, with the transaction expected to close by the end of the same year.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] This led to the Competition and Markets Authority of the United Kingdom launching an investigation into the acquisition in late 2024.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] The deal closed on February 27, 2025 for $6.4 billion after receiving the necessary regulatory approvals.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] HashiCorp provides a suite of tools intended to support the development and deployment of large-scale service-oriented software installations.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Each tool is aimed at specific stages in the life cycle of a software application, with a focus on automation.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Many have a plugin-oriented architecture in order to provide integration with third-party technologies and services.
[src:hashicorp-consul/hashicorp] Additional proprietary features for some of these tools are offered commercially and are aimed at enterprise customers.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-discovery] Service discovery requires a common language to allow software agents to make use of one another's services without the need for continuous user intervention.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:hashicorp-consul/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
